#A. Arrays (15 Questions)
(These build your foundation for coding interviews)
Find the max and min in an array.
Find the second largest element in an array.
Reverse an array in-place.
Move all zeros to the end of the array.
Check if the array is sorted.
Find the missing number from 1..N.
Find the duplicate number when only one duplicate exists.
Rotate array by K steps (using reverse approach).
Merge two sorted arrays.
Find intersection of two arrays.
Count frequencies of all elements (using HashMap).
Find the majority element (Boyer-Moore beginner version).
Find the peak element (binary search type).
Kadane’s Algorithm – Maximum subarray sum.
Find pair sum = K using two pointers.

#B. Strings (10 Questions)
(Simple but very frequently asked)
Reverse a string.
Check if a string is a palindrome.
Count vowels & consonants.
Remove duplicate characters from a string.
Check if two strings are anagrams.
Find the first non-repeating character.
Count frequency of each character.
Convert lowercase → uppercase without using built-in.
Longest common prefix in an array of strings.
Check if two strings differ by one edit distance.

#C. Two Pointers & Sliding Window (8 Questions)
Longest substring without repeating characters.
Longest substring with K distinct characters (easy version).
Check if a string is a permutation of another substring.
Minimum size subarray sum (beginner sliding window).
Container With Most Water (famous 2-pointer).
Sort array of 0s, 1s, 2s (Dutch Flag easy version).
Find squares of sorted array.
Find triplets with sum = 0 (3-sum beginner version).

#D. Recursion Basics (6 Questions)
(Beginner-friendly recursion practice)
Factorial using recursion.
Fibonacci using recursion (and optimized DP version optional).
Reverse a string using recursion.
Sum of digits using recursion.
Power of a number (fast exponentiation – easy version).
Print all subsets of a given array (recursion intro).

#E. Linked List (10 Questions)
(Practices common interview patterns but not too hard)
Implement a singly linked list.
Insert at head, tail, and delete a value.
Find middle of linked list (slow/fast).
Detect cycle in linked list (Floyd’s – beginner version).
Reverse a linked list (iterative).
Reverse a linked list (recursive).
Merge two sorted linked lists.
Remove duplicates in a sorted linked list.
Check if linked list is palindrome (easy logic).
Remove Nth node from end (two-pointer easy version).

#F. Stack & Queue (6 Questions)
Implement stack using array.
Implement queue using array.
Valid parentheses (using stack).
Evaluate postfix expression (beginner version).
Next greater element (easy stack version).
Implement min stack (store pairs).

#G. Binary Search (8 Questions)
(Perfect level for you right now)
Binary search basic implementation.
Search in rotated sorted array (beginner version).
Find first/last occurrence of an element.
Floor and Ceiling of a number.
Search insert position.
Find peak element (binary search version).
Square root of a number using binary search.
Find smallest letter greater than target.

#H. Sorting Concepts (4 Questions)
Bubble sort (optimized).
Selection sort.
Insertion sort.
Merge sort (only conceptual + simple implementation).

#I. Basic OOP & Java Concepts (6 Questions)
(Not coding-heavy but MUST know)
Implement a class Student with Encapsulation (getters/setters).
Demonstrate constructor overloading.
Demonstrate method overloading and overriding.
Create interface + class implementing it.
Implement a simple BankAccount class (deposit/withdraw).
Override equals() and hashCode() in a simple class.